scopecontent.p:
Series II primarily documents the sale and development, in the late nineteenth century, of Strawberry Hill, Horace Walpole's estate in Twickenham, and Houghton Hall, the family's estate in Norfolk, through printed auction prospectuses, maps, and site plans issued by London firms marketing the properties. Material is present too for Little Strawberry Hill, which was at times offered separately from Strawberry Hill, as well as the family's home at 15 Berkeley Square, London. Also here are engraved views and floor plans of Strawberry Hill and Houghton Hall removed from publications, a photograph of Houghton Hall (1865, a plate from 
                     Norfolk Photographically Illustrated
                  ), prints of Strawberry Hill interiors, chimneys, and collection objects (plates engraved for 
                     A Description of the Villa of Mr. Horace Walpole
                  ), and newspaper clippings describing the estates. In addition, there are views of homes of the Berry, Chute, and Townsend families, and another Walpole ancestral home, Wolterton Hall in Norfolk.
